Despite the gridlock in and out of Apapa occasioned by poor access roads, trade volume recorded by Tin-Can Island Command of the Nigeria Customs Service increased by 52.28 percent between January and June 2019. Export commodities recorded by the command also rose from the previous 118,452.87 metric tons of agricultural and solid minerals in 2018 to 150,930.7 metric tons in the first half of 2019. Stakeholders are of the opinion that the volume of export trade recorded by the command would have risen above 118,452.87 metric tons but for improper documentation on the part of exporters. OVER 5,000 NIGERIAN MEN HAVE  OVERCOME POOR BEDROOM PERFORMANCE SYNDROME DUE TO THIS BRILLIANT DISCOVERY. CLICK HERE TO KNOW MORE Already, there are strong indications that the command may record a remarkable increase in trade volume for imports as shown by the performance index of the command. The Customs Area Controller, Tin-Can Island Command, Apapa, Comptroller MBA Musa credited his command’s high performance to renewed enthusiasm and development of Standard Operational Procedures (SOP) for operational efficiency, noting the command’s major paradigm shift, particularly in the  area of statutory functions. Comptroller  Musa disclosed that his command generated N68.8bn from 150,930.7 metric tons of agricultural produce and other items exported from the country between January and June 2019. He said that was against a total of 118,452.87 metric tons of export valued at N63m recorded during the same period in 2018. This is even as he revealed that his command also generated N179.3bn from import between January and July 10, 2019. He noted that a comparative review of the preceding year 2018 indicated that the command realized N172.5 billion representing 52.28 percent increase of its annual target with a difference of N6.8 billion.  Export through Tincan grow  to N29bn in Q1 – Customs Tin Can Port’s traffic  of horror NCS generates N61.7bn at Tin-Can Port in Q1 2015, says Spokesman Dear E